<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="_u1_m2_planes_inline_digt"><title>tutor</title><page id="b3fbc7e282b14b46a9c22351f319bb06"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><question id="q1"><body><p id="abd4c48c654664087bbcbb8e87de9b690">What plane is shown in the adjoining scan?</p></body><multiple_choice id="b5461161371643059c16676344c3cba5" labels="false" select="single" shuffle="true"><choice value="A">transverse</choice><choice value="B">coronal</choice><choice value="C">sagittal</choice></multiple_choice><part id="i51225a980aef41718f4c1bf7b25aa746"><skillref idref="_u1_orientation_planes_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="ac7ff4e903842447b8d6f9ebf65a1148c">Incorrect. A transverse view is one in which the specimen is cut into superior and inferior sections. This is a view of the right side of the head.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab8b809b7d0d7415c86742bfb9630d55d">Incorrect. A coronal view observes the specimen from the anterior or posterior side. This is a view of the right side of the head.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="aec1387d53799433f98ad1a2ce350314d">Correct. Notice that you can see the entire head and brain in this view. You are looking at the right side of the head from a medial view.</p></feedback></response></part></question></page></assessment>
